<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / Referendum promise eases unionist fears: Paisley's deputy
welcomes 'step forward'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major's explicit commit-ment to submitting any decision on the
future of Northern Ireland to a referendum in the province appeared last
night to have reassured several leading unionists.
It was also welcomed by Mr Albert Reynolds, prime minister of the Irish
Republic, and Mr Dick Spring, the republic's foreign minister.
Mr Peter Robinson, deputy leader of the hardline Democratic Unionist party,
who has been strongly critical of the peace initiative, described the
commitment as a 'step forward'.
Just over a week ago after a stormy meeting with Mr Major in Downing Street
he joined his leader the Rev Ian Paisley in accusing the government of
reaching secret deals with the IRA.
Last night, however, Mr Robinson indicated that he was prepared to put such
conspiracy talk behind him. 'The prime minister's announcement has taken us
beyond that . . . the issue is now one of consent,' he said.
Mr Reg Empey, a former mayor of Belfast, described the government's
announcement as a 'very major step forward' which would encourage unionists
to commit themselves more fully to the peace process. 'For the first time,
it opens up the possibility of people participating in their future,' he
said.
Mr Reynolds said the holding of referendums north and south of the border on
any substantial new agreement would be a 'logical development of the Downing
Street peace declaration'.
He was supported by Mr Spring, who said Mr Major's commitment was 'in line
with the position in our government programme that the final outcome of such
negotiations would need to be acceptable to the people, north and south'.
He added: 'It will, I hope, reassure those who at present hesitate to engage
in the process of political dialogue, which is so necessary if the potential
of the present situation is to be realised.'
The holding of a referendum was implied in the joint Anglo-Irish declaration
last December, but yesterday's more specific reference was aimed at
reassuring unionist opinion against the background of threats of loyalist
paramilitary violence.
Since the IRA ceasefire was announced some unionist politicians have been
claiming that Sinn Fein and the IRA are dictating the pace and scope of the
peace process.
Some unionists last night still said that the government had made
unjustified concessions to the IRA by lifting the broadcasting ban and some
border controls.
Mr Ken Maginnis, Ulster Unionist MP for Fermanagh and South Tyrone, one of
the areas affected by the opening of border controls, said last night: 'Law
abiding people . . . quite simply do not want concessions given to Sinn Fein
without some certainty that a ceasefire is permanent.'
</TEXT>
