<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 94 / Kaiser averts Ghana smelter shutdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ghanaian power authorities and Kaiser Aluminium Company have averted a total
shutdown of Kaiser's big Volta River valley smelter while negotiations over
the company's access to cheap hydropower in the region continue.
In an agreement announced yesterday, Kaiser will close one of the smelter's
potlines, or about 40,000 tonnes of annual capacity, tomorrow.
Depending on conditions, another 20,000 tonnes of capacity could be shut by
year-end. This would reduce the Ghanaian smelter's annual production to
about 80,000 tonnes.
Kaiser, responding to low water levels, trimmed about 30 per cent of the
smelter's output last spring.
A prolonged drought in Ghana has lowered water levels in the Volta Lake
region, and caused the Volta River Authority to notify Kaiser earlier this
month that it would be forced to cut off power to the smelter on September
10. The smelter produces 200,000 tonnes of aluminium a year when operating
at full capacity.
Kaiser appealed against the decision, saying that the action was premature.
The company maintained that lake levels had begun to rise, and that the
country's rainy season had not ended.
'We have agreed to talk with officials at the Volta River Authority in late
October to reassess the situation,' said Mr Scott Lamb, a Kaiser spokesman.
'At that time we will review the rainfall situation, discuss compensation
due the company for the curtailment, and explore other matters related to
the power contract.'
In addition to the smelter, the Volta River Authority must meet the
electricity needs of local residents and small industrial concerns.
</TEXT>
