<PROFILE>_AN-EIPC9AFHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940916
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / International Company News: Fiat sells seat-making unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fiat, the Italian vehicles group, is taking another step to outsource more
motor components with the Dollars 160m sale of its car seat-making
activities to Lear Seating of the US.
Under a preliminary deal announced yesterday, Lear will acquire Fiat's
Italian-based Sepi seat-making subsidiary.
Sepi will continue, under Lear's ownership, to supply Fiat's Italian car
plants.
However, Lear will also use the operations to supply markets in eastern
Europe and Latin America.
The deal is in line with a growing trend by leading car producers to
concentrate on vehicle assembly, leaving many component supplies to
independent producers, which can achieve greater economies of scale by
supplying several other vehicle makers simultaneously.
Two months ago, Fiat in effect disengaged itself from another important
components sector, the constant velocity joints and driveshafts essential to
all front-wheel-drive cars, in a deal with GKN, the UK industrial group.
GKN agreed to invest Pounds 50m (Dollars 77.5m) in a joint venture with Fiat
which will supply the Italian vehicle maker with drive-line components from
a new factory near Florence.
GKN holds 85 per cent and management control of the venture, which has taken
over Fiat's own business which had been making the components.
The Lear-Sepi and GKN ventures provide for non-Fiat customers to be
supplied.
Sepi had 1993 sales of about Dollars 350m and produced seats for more than
1m vehicles. It has about 1,800 employees.
The Sepi agreement is subject to completion of a due-diligence review and
other conditions.
However, when completed the deal 'will increase our global market share and
further strengthen our European position as well as allow us the opportunity
to expand with Fiat in eastern Europe and South America,' said Mr Ken Way,
Lear's chairman and chief executive.
</TEXT>
