<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Pounds 234m so far for B&amp;C creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Creditors to British &amp; Commonwealth, the collapsed financial services group,
are to receive interim payments of Pounds 95m, the administrators said
yesterday.
Creditors to British &amp; Commonwealth Holdings will receive a dividend of 5p
in the pound, bringing their total received so far to 20p or Pounds 234m.
Creditors to B&amp;C Group Finance, a subsidiary, will get 2p in the pound,
bringing their total to 30p or Pounds 223m. Creditors to Group Finance will
receive a further 3p in the pound or Pounds 22m from the sale earlier this
week of shares in Celltech, a biotechnology company in which it had a stake.
Other dividends have come through the sale of the shares of Exco, the
group's money-broking subsidiary which was floated in July.
The details came in a report circulated to creditors by Stephen Adamson,
Nigel Hamilton and Gareth Hughes, the administrators from accountants Ernst
&amp; Young.
The administrators have not changed their estimate that total dividends will
be about Pounds 1bn. There was no mention of progress on a number of
threatened and current legal actions designed to gather additional money for
credit-ors.
Directors and advisers were subject to strong criticism in a Department of
Trade &amp; Industry inspectors' report published last month.
