<PROFILE>_AN-EIPC9AC6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940916
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Those who thought that John Betjeman was a rather ducky little poet chiefly
concerned with exulting in the glories of trolley buses and Bourne and
Hollingsworth, will have realised their mistake if they have been watching
The Lost Betjemans on C4. He was, no doubt, fascinated by middle-class
gentility and old-worldliness. But the streak of misanthropy and depression
(about as wide as Balham High Street) which was so close below the surface
of his work has been unmistakable here. Tonight's programme records his
visits to Weston-super-
Mare and Bath in 1962 (8.00). My candidate for the murderer in 'Master Of
The Moor', ITV's Ruth Rendell Mystery, is Stephen's old Dadda. So how do I
explain the sinister figure in the cloak? Probably the detective, Manciple,
acting out some mad obsession. Or, since it is always referred to as 'he'
but is hooded, a woman. Do I really care? Not much, but enough to watch this
final episode (9.00). The commentary in the first part of The Longest Walk
was so set upon emphasising the faults of round-the-world walker Ffyona
Campbell that everyone must be rooting for her. Perhaps that was the idea
(9.30 BBC2).
</TEXT>
