<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / M-way toll trials soon: 'Enormous' contract triggers
responses from 29 consortia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Twenty-nine consortia representing more than 70 companies from around the
world have responded to the government's call for proposals for an
electronic tolling system for Britain's motorways.
Most proposals would involve gantries to read units fitted in vehicles.
Others would depend on the satellite tracking of vehicle movements, Mr John
Watts, roads minister, said yesterday.
The government hopes to introduce tolls on the 1,900-mile motorway network
by 1998. Charging cars 1.5p a mile and trucks 4.5p would raise Pounds 700m a
year for road improvements.
The proposed systems will be evaluated in the next four months with the aim
of running trials on a test track and on motorways next year. The government
will then draw up a technical specification of the system it wants and put
the contract out to tender in spring 1996.
Mr Watts said: 'Any contract we let would be enormous. We want to develop a
specification which can be sold around the world.'
It is likely that the contract would be let to more than one consortium
because of its size. One option under consideration is for the winning
companies not to be paid on completion but for them to recoup their outlay
from tolls.
Mr Watts denied that the government had ignored criticisms in a report by
the Conservative-dominated Commons transport committee which was published
last month.
The MPs said the government's arguments for tolls were unconvincing and
suggested an increase in fuel duty would be easier and cheaper to collect.
Mr Watts said the government was considering its response but had to
continue with its preparations.
Proposals had come from companies in Europe, the Far East and North America,
but nearly all of the consortia had a British member. Well over half of the
consortia had a strong base in the UK, sometimes through foreign ownership
of British companies.
Twenty-four of the systems proposed would involve a monitor mounted on a
gantry identifying and charging vehicles passing underneath. Most of these
systems depend on microwave links, but two use infra-red and one a laser.
These systems could debit a 'smart card' or record a vehicle for billing
later.
Three companies have proposed satellite-based systems which would debit a
smart card and would not require roadside gantries.
Among companies which have put forward proposals are Unipass, a UK company;
a group comprising News Datacom (UK) and CSEE Peage of France; and a
consortium consisting of British Telecommunications and AT/Comm, a US
manufacturer. Racal Radio, part of Racal Electronics, has devised a
number-plate recognition system.
</TEXT>
