<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Labour woos small businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday stepped up its drive to win the support of small business
with the release of a comprehensive package of financing and development
proposals.
The launch of the proposals at Westminster reflects growing contacts between
Labour and small business as the party seeks to exploit dis-illusionment
with the government.
It follows an initiative begun under former leader John Smith and a regional
tour last year by Labour's trade and industry team led by Mr Robin Cook.
Mr Derek Fatchett, industry spokesman, said the Conservatives had taken the
traditional loyalty of small business for granted.
He said: 'The last five years have seen over 200,000 businesses driven into
bankruptcy, debt levels rise to record levels, good new ideas starved of
financial support and thousands of dreams shattered.
'It is little wonder that support for the Conservatives among the small
business community is lower than at any other point and has more than halved
in the last 10 years.'
The package of policies includes the establishment of a business development
bank to provide long-term finance for small businesses, pressure on large
companies and public agencies to pay debts more quickly, and a legal right
to interest on late payments.
The party promises a moratorium law to give financially troubled small
companies a breathing space before bankruptcy action, and tax changes to
encourage greater reinvestment of profits.
There would be a network of regional development agencies for small
companies, and public procurement policies would be reviewed to encourage
the development of high-tech small and medium-size enterprises.
The proposals, most of which have been aired by Labour in the past 18
months, were given a cautious welcome by Mr Ian Handford, policy unit
chairman of the Federation of Small Businesses.
Mr Handford said small-business people were not 'natural Labour voters'. He
said Labour was 'looking at a sector which they haven't looked at before'.
</TEXT>
