<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Loans chief convicted of fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The former chairman of Castlegate Securities, a Reading-based loan
management company, was yesterday convicted of fraudulently mishandling the
funds of investors who lost Pounds 35m, John Mason writes.
A jury at Oxford crown court found Mr Roy Wharton guilty of two charges of
fraudulent trading after a three-month trial brought by the Serious Fraud
Office.
The court heard how Castlegate grew from a small unsecured lending business
into a group of companies managing secured loans totalling almost Pounds 44m
by the time they were liquidated in December 1990.
Institutional and private investors provided the backing for the group, but
it was the private investors, mainly retired and elderly people, who bore
the brunt of the Pounds 35m losses when Castlegate collapsed. Many lost
their savings and some their homes.
Investors had been assured that Castlegate would make up any shortfall
suffered by one of its subsidiaries. But all assurances from the company
proved false. Mr Wharton's speculative lending strategy meant that the
companies bore the brunt of the risk while he reaped the financial benefits.
The prosecution at his trial described his method as 'a sophisticated game
of pass-the-parcel'.
To keep Castlegate afloat Mr Wharton falsely inflated the values of
properties under his control to expand his lending. He was remanded in
custody until sentencing on October 7.
</TEXT>
