FT  16 SEP 94 / Improved GMTV avoids sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission decided yesterday not to impose
sanctions on GMTV, the commercial television breakfast station, because
there had been a 'demonstrable improvement' in its service.
The ITC had warned that unless there was an improvement by this month formal
sanctions might be imposed, which could include fines.
As part of its review of GMTV's first year on air the ITC had judged its
performance to have been unsatisfactory. The commission said there had been
significant shortfalls in the required amount of news, current affairs and
children's information. There was also concern about the quality of some
programming.
GMTV is owned by Granada, Carlton Communications, the Guardian Media Group,
Scottish Television and the Walt Disney Company.
Following the introduction in February of an early morning news programme
produced by Reuters and the addition of other current affairs output, the
ITC said yesterday it was satisfied that the company was meeting licence
requirements.
It added: 'Despite these improvements, the commission will be looking for
further evidence of sustained quality in GMTV's children's programmes during
the remainder of the year.'
