<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / The spirit of glasnost reaches the Highlands: Local
Enterprise Companies are trying a policy of openness in handing out grants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The West Highland Free Press, a weekly newspaper, reported recently that Mrs
Jean Threlfall of Ardvasar in Skye had been given a grant of Pounds 400 for
her business breeding Skye terriers. The money was spent on new kennels.
Last month the paper recorded that the fish processor Johnston Seafayre of
Stornoway, Lewis, had been granted Pounds 42,000 for working capital, and
that Lady Clare Macdonald, the Skye hotelier and cookery writer, had been
given Pounds 4,500 to expand her cookery demonstration business.
These and countless other modest pieces of news have been appearing
regularly in newspapers in northern Scotland since April, when the 10 Local
Enterprise Companies (Lecs) which have been operating in the area for three
years adopted a policy of almost total disclosure of their activities.
No longer can the Highland Lecs, the employer-led economic development
bodies, cite 'commercial confidentiality' as a reason for keeping most
transactions secret, unless the release of information would harm a
company's competitive position.
Each month the Lecs produce a list of businesses and people to whom they
have given grants, even down to individuals receiving training grants, and
newspapers are free to publish it.
The policy, called 'accountability through openness', was introduced by the
Lecs and their parent body, Highlands and Islands Enterprise, in response to
criticism that the Lecs were unaccountable to the people they served.
The same claim is made about the Lecs reporting to Scottish Enterprise in
the Lowlands, as well as about the Training and Enterprise Councils, which
deliver government training schemes in England and Wales and have a
development role.
Critics, notably in the Labour party, argue that none of the people on the
boards of Lecs or Tecs has had to face democratic election, and that they
use the 'figleaf' of commercial confidentiality to conceal what they are
doing.
In Scotland there is a widespread perception that the Lecs, with their
boards largely composed of businessmen, are a kind of old boy's club,
occasionally handing out public money in grants and loans to businesses
which involve the directors themselves. Lecs certainly do have dealings with
companies run by their directors, but such transactions are governed by
strict rules.
However, the problem of conflicts of interest is particularly acute in the
Highlands because most Lecs cover areas with only a few thousand
inhabitants.
High-profile local businessmen sit on the boards of their Lecs and some also
have commercial dealings with them, although these must be arranged at arm's
length and declared in the Lec's annual report.
HIE acknowledges that 'it has taken time to gain local support for the
Lecs', but points out that the network has suffered 'no instance whatsoever
of misdealing involving Lec directors'.
As it is unable to do anything about its structure, which is accountable to
parliament through the Scottish secretary, it is trying to achieve broader
accountability by being open about its activities.
Caithness and Sutherland Enterprise started its own glasnost six months
before the policy was adopted by the rest of the network. It produces a
10-page monthly overview and a full list of grants.
Mr Neil Money, deputy chief executive, said: 'What we wanted was make people
aware of what we do. We tell people when they apply for grants their names
will be published, though we say we'll withhold them for a time if it's
commercially sensitive.
'There's no evidence that people have been put off from applying. In fact
the reverse is the case. People have come to us because they have discovered
grants are available.'
Mr Iain Robertson, chief executive of HIE, believes that the openness policy
is assisting economic development. He said: 'People look at the lists and
they read what's going on in their areas, they get ideas and they come to us
for help. It's opening up the Highlands.'
But although Mr Henry McLeish, deputy shadow Scottish secretary, says that
'in principle' he would favour the same openness policy being adopted by
Lecs in the Lowlands, Scottish Enterprise says the idea is 'not
appropriate'.
It points out that a large part of the activity of the Highland Lecs
consists of handing out relatively small grants, many of them only available
to people and businesses in the region because of its special needs.
This type of activity, they say, makes up only a tiny fraction of the
activity of Lecs in lowland Scotland, which are mainly involved in
large-scale training, and in striking agreements with private-sector
companies in areas such as property development, the creation of new
products, and attracting investors. In those cases it believes commercial
confidentiality is usually essential.
Mr Des Bonnar, chief executive of Lothian and Edinburgh Enterprise, said:
'It's a question of balancing transparency with effectiveness and acting as
reliable partners of private sector companies.
'Would you do a deal with a company which told you that the transaction
would automatically be in the public domain by the end of the month?'
For Mr McLeish, the attitude of Scottish Enterprise typifies 'a culture of
secrecy which is bringing it more criticism than it actually deserves'.
</TEXT>
