<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Food sales outstrip other sectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain is enjoying a well-fed economic recovery.
Yesterday's announcement of a surprise 0.3 per cent fall in retail sales
volumes between July and August attracted attention in financial markets.
But more detailed, seasonally adjusted figures from the Central Statistical
Office showed mixed fortunes among different categories of retail outlet.
On the basis of three-month figures, which the government considers a better
guide to trends, sales by food retailers far outstripped those of other
types of retailer and the retail sector as a whole.
The Central Statistical Office reported that food retailers increased their
sales volumes by a seasonally adjusted 1.5 per cent between June and August
compared with the previous three months. Sales volumes of mixed businesses
such as department stores and mail order houses were 0.3 per cent higher and
specialist non-food retailers 0.1 per cent lower.
Compared with June to August last year volume sales rose 5.4 per cent in the
case of food retailers, more than twice the 2.5 per cent year-on-year growth
of mixed retail businesses and three times the 1.8 per cent annual sales
growth of non-food retailers.
Clothing and footwear merchants fared best among the non-food retailers,
boosting their volume sales 1.1 per cent in the latest three months compared
with March to May and 4.8 per cent compared with June to August last year.
Retailers of household goods reported a 0.1 per cent fall in volume sales in
the latest three months but growth of 3.4 per cent over the year. The CSO
said that other non-food retailers such as jewellers, chemists, tobacconists
and booksellers suffered an overall fall of 0.9 per cent in sales volumes in
the latest three months and a 1.9 per cent fall compared with June to August
last year.
The retail sector as a whole expanded its volume sales by 0.6 per cent
between June and August compared with March to May and 3.3 per cent compared
with the three months to the end of August last year.
The Retail Consortium, which says it represents 90 per cent of the retail
industry, reported strong year-on-year growth in sales of fresh produce,
poultry and fish in August.
</TEXT>
