<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Limit on teachers' hours vetoed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, yesterday ruled out putting
limits on teachers' working hours or on class sizes.
Her statement, made in evidence to the School Teachers' Review Body, the
quango which sets pay and conditions each year, provoked an angry reaction
from teaching unions.
The traditionally moderate Association of Teachers and Lecturers also
submitted evidence to the review body, and said the 'highest priority'
should be attached to 'steps that relieve workload pressure'. A survey for
the union suggested teachers worked an average of 54 hours a week.
Mrs Shephard said workload surveys were 'notoriously difficult to conduct'.
She added that a 1992 survey by the Department for Education had suggested
teachers worked an average of 42.1 hours a week and that 'it would be
dangerous to rely too heavily on any one survey'.
The department's evidence made no recommendations on the overall level of
pay, but suggested that teachers returning to the profession after a career
break or moving jobs might lose their entitlement to extra 'experience' pay
points. Mrs Shephard said: 'Some experienced teachers believe that the cost
of their past experience works against them.'
Mr Peter Smith, general secretary of the ATL, which called for a 6 per cent
overall pay rise, said: 'This is like trying to get blood out of a stone. On
the one hand the government demands more effort from already overloaded
teachers, while on the other hand there is no reward for hard work and
dedication in the classroom.'
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, said:
'By refusing to consider ways of reducing teachers' workload the government
is undermining its own stated aim of improved pupil performance.'
</TEXT>
