<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Public pay bill 'to rise 2% despite freeze'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The public-sector pay bill for this year is likely to rise by at least 2 per
cent in spite of the government's desire for a freeze, says a leading pay
analyst.
Mr Chris Trinder, research director of the Public Finance Foundation, said
large areas of the public sector, particularly education, were likely to
have significant overruns.
His comments follow confirmation by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, of
the government's desire for a further year's freezing of the public-sector
pay bill.
Mr Clarke, in his written submission to the pay review bodies, which cover
about 1.4m of the 5m public-sector workers, indirectly criticised last
year's relatively high pay review body settlements. He said: 'The government
remains concerned that cumulatively over the years review body settlements
have more than matched most other public-sector groups.'
Yet the submission also stressed flexibility. 'Recommendations should take
account of the particular circumstances of each group and the need to
promote the development of performance pay and other flexibilities as
appropriate,' he said.
Mr Trinder said yesterday that the public-sector pay bill rose 1 per cent
last year in spite of the fact that pay rises were limited to 1.5 per cent
and 327,000 jobs were shed.
This year the average pay rise in the public sector is likely to be about
2.5 per cent and job losses are likely to be considerably below last year's
figure. Mr Trinder said: 'That means it is almost certain that the increase
in the pay bill will be well above last year's'
The government has relaxed its original ban on cross-subsidising pay bill
increases from general running costs, which means that the pay bill overrun
is likely to hit services. About 58 per cent of public-sector running costs
are wages.
Mr Trinder said the public-sector pay bill freeze appeared to be becoming
more rather than less flexible. He also warned that a growing divergence
between public and private-sector pay could create recruitment problems in
the public sector. Last year, when the public-sector pay bill rose only 1
per cent, the private-sector pay bill rose 3.9 per cent.
Real wage growth - on top of inflation - averaged 1.4 per cent during the
1993-94 pay round, covering both the public and private sector. That was
lower than the 2.2 per cent for 1992-1993 but higher than the 1.25 per cent
average of the previous three years.
Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union, yesterday
accused the government of picking on public-sector workers.
</TEXT>
