<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / ITC to readvertise licence for Channel 5
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission yesterday took a formal decision to
readvertise a licence for Channel 5, a new terrestrial television channel.
A number of corporations have expressed interest in bidding for what some
see as the last important broadcasting opportunity using existing technology
in a large European market.
The commission said it could not give precise figures for Channel 5's
population coverage since the government had decided to reserve channel 35 -
one of two channels designated for Channel 5 - to the further development of
digital terrestrial television.
The effect of the government decision was to reduce the minimum coverage for
Channel 5 from 74 per cent to 52 per cent of the population.
However, with additional frequencies identified by ITC engineers this could
rise to a maximum of about 70 per cent. The new frequencies will need
national and international clearances. In addition digital simultaneous
broadcasting could increase coverage further to between 80 per cent and 95
per cent. Applicants will have to submit a business plan for the maximum
potential coverage. They will then have to provide plans for lower possible
coverage - 60 per cent or even 52 per cent.
Possible applicants are CanWest, which is backed by large quoted British
companies, the Virgin Group, Yorkshire-Tyne Tees television, NBC and a group
linking Time Warner, MAI and Pearson, owner of the Financial Times.
The licence, to be awarded by competitive tender, will be advertised on
November 1 with a closing date six months later. This would imply that
Channel 5 would not launch until well into 1996.
When the ITC first advertised the licence in April 1992 there was little
interest and the one applicant - a Thames Television consortium - was
rejected mainly because of poor investor commitment.
GMTV reprieve, Page 11
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
