<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Sri Lanka in push to end war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MERVYN DE SILVA and STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COLOMBO, NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sri Lanka's new government is making a concerted effort to end the civil war
that has plagued the country since the mid-1980s, the coalition's newly
appointed chief economic adviser said yesterday.
'We have to end this war. The prime minister is absolutely right in tackling
that problem first,' said Mr Lal Jayawardena, who this week joined Premier
Chandrika Kumaratunga's administration.
Mrs Chandrika has offered to negotiate a peace settlement with the
separatist Tamil 'Tiger' guerrillas fighting for an independent homeland for
ethnic Tamils.
Mr Jayawardena said Sri Lanka was spending about Rs20bn (Pounds 262m) a year
on the war, the equivalent of 4 per cent of GDP, plus a further Rs3bn on
war-related problems. The peace dividend could be substantial.
A former treasury secretary, hedismissed suggestions that left-wing members
of Mrs Kumaratunga's centre-left coalition could force adoption of socialist
policies. The government would not change the previous conservative
administration's labour policies, nor would there be any nationalisation or
expropriation of private property. The government was committed to
export-led growth including export-oriented services, he added.
