<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Crimean parliament seeks government resignation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW KAMINSKI and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The parliament of the autonomous Crimean peninsula in Ukraine has called for
the resignation of the regional government, Matthew Kaminski and agencies
report. Before the no-confidence vote Mr Yevgeny Saburov, deputy prime
minister and acting head of government, tendered his resignation, saying he
did not 'see the possibility of working further in a constructive way if
this situation continues'. President Yuri Meshkov refused to accept the
resignation.
'Saburov's still the government chief,' said Mr Sergei Nikolsky, agriculture
minister. 'But the way things are going we will all be out of a job quite
soon.'
The no-confidence vote follows a confrontation over the parliament's
decision to strip President Meshkov of many of his powers. The president,
elected on a populist ticket in January, announced on Sunday he was
disbanding parliament and introducing presidential rule. But the president's
gesture of reopening parliament two days later encouraged MPs to demand the
dismissal of the government before it would begin talks over the president's
powers.
</TEXT>
