<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 94 / Raytheon's UK jet plants set to close
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Raytheon of the US is to close the corporate jet business it bought from
British Aerospace and transfer work to the US with the loss of 850 UK jobs
over the next three years.
The decision provoked strong protests yesterday after its announcement by
the US industrial group which acquired the BAe business for Pounds 250m last
year.
Union and Labour party representatives called on Mr Michael Heseltine, the
trade and industry secretary, to intervene to stop Raytheon closing its
facilities at Broughton, near Chester, and Hatfield, Hertfordshire. Raytheon
currently leases both plants from BAe.
The US company, which is also suspending production of the Hawker 1000
business jet and slowing production of the smaller Hawker 800 jet, said the
move reflected difficulties in the recession-hit corporate jet market.
'The timing of this decision is principally driven by the current weak
market conditions and substantiated by the results of a recently completed
study by Raytheon after it acquired Corporate Jets from British Aerospace,'
the US company said. It added it was immediately cutting 170 out of 550 jobs
at Broughton, where Hawker business jets are assembled, and 143 out of 300
jobs at its Hatfield design, engineering and marketing facility. The
remaining jobs at both plants will go by 1997, although several UK employees
will be offered jobs in the US.
Raytheon is also cutting 630 jobs in the US as part of the overall
rationalisation of its corporate aircraft activities. The company is merging
its Beech Aircraft subsidiary with the former BAe corporate jet activities
it acquired last year into the Raytheon Aircraft Company based in Wichita,
Kansas.
Raytheon said final assembly of Hawker jets would start being moved from
Broughton to Wichita next year and be completed in 1997.
There were fears yesterday that the decision could also have repercussions
on jobs at BAe's Airbus division at Chester, which supplies wings and
fuselage sections for Hawker jets. About 470 BAe Airbus staff are employed
on Hawker activities.
Apart from poor market conditions, Raytheon said its study of its aircraft
businesses concluded that merging Hawker and Beech aircraft production would
achieve significant cost savings.
The company is suspending production of the Hawker 1000 to improve the model
and boost its sales prospects. Raytheon renamed the BAe corporate jets
Hawker when it took over the company.
Since the sale, former BAe employees had worried that Raytheon would
transfer production to the US. But the announcement still came as a shock to
staff. Mr Tony Lloyd, Labour's employment spokesman, said it was 'outrageous
that an American company can move in, buy an order book and then close down
forever the plants with the consequences for skilled employment'.
</TEXT>
