<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Perplexing economic data
ignored by Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices made some progress yesterday afternoon in spite of mixed
economic news and a lethargic bond market, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 15.47 higher at 3,895.33, thanks
in part to computer-guided buy programs which lifted some blue chips late in
the session. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 1.28 ahead at 468.80 and the
Nasdaq composite added 2.77 at 768.60. NYSE volume was 296m shares.
During the morning, the thin activity suggested that investors were
perplexed about the current state of the economy. The day's economic news
may have served to compound the uncertainty.
The Commerce Department announced a 0.8 per cent increase in August retail
sales, a weaker result than the 1.0 per cent gain which had been forecast.
But in spite of the recent anxiety over inflation, the market could gain
little comfort from the report. Retail sales, excluding cars, came in at 0.7
per cent, against expectations of a 0.4 per cent gain. This indicated that
activity was stronger than suggested by the headline figure.
Stocks held steady on the release of the data, with the bond market offering
no guidance whatsoever. With Treasuries showing no change, share prices
meandered within a narrow range throughout the morning.
The release of the Federal Reserve's Beige Book report on economic
conditions at midday elicited a muted reaction, too. In finding that the
economy continued to grow at a moderate pace, the Fed told a story with
which Wall Street was already familiar.
Still, the Dow industrials built up some momentum during the afternoon.
Caterpillar rose Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 55 1/8 , Coca-Cola Dollars 1 1/8
to Dollars 47 1/8 and United Technology Dollars 1 to Dollars 64 1/4.
American Express put on Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 31 7/8 , buoyed no doubt by
its recent moves in the travel and credit card businesses.
Heightened speculation on the future of the NBC broadcasting network
influenced the share prices of the companies involved.
Walt Disney, which was reported to be in talks on acquiring NBC from General
Electric, slipped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 41 1/4 . GE rose Dollars  3/4 to
Dollars 50 1/4 . Time Warner, also said to be discussing a possible deal,
edged down Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 36.
Following Kohlberg Kravis Roberts' Dollars 2bn bid for Borden, Quaker Oats
inspired early buying from those who consider the food group as a likely
target. The stock had been up Dollars 2 3/4 by midday, but receded later to
Dollars 79 1/2 for a gain of Dollars 3/8.
CompUSA, an electronics retailer, jumped Dollars 2 1/4, or 24 per cent, to
Dollars 12 amid reports of insider buying and a strong sales outlook.
Canada
Toronto sought fresh impetus in the aftermath of the Quebec election as the
market also awaited a speech later in the day in which Quebec's president
elect Jacques Parizeau was expected to lay out his sovereignty plans.
In spite of a 0.9 per cent decline in the heavily weighted gold shares
sub-index, the TSE 300 composite index was a slight 0.81 of a point firmer
at the close at 4,345.03, while gaining issues outnumbered losers by 371 to
360. Volume came to a moderate 56.1m shares.
Brazil
Equities in Sao Paulo, after early firmness, closed a net 0.63 per cent down
in heavy trade, rattled by unconfirmed rumours late in the session that some
small financial institutions and a state-owned bank faced liquidity
difficulties. The Bovespa index was finally off 346 points at 54,764.
'Shares dropped on rumours that a major state bank was having problems in
squaring its position at the central bank,' a broker at a leading commercial
bank said. 'If that is true, other small banks would be affected as well.'
Analysts said recent central bank action, aimed at squeezing the market's
liquidity, was the cause of the rumours. Chart analysts said investors could
also have used the rumours as an excuse to cash profits after stocks had
risen 86 per cent so far this year.
The market was also keeping a close eye on Telebras' performance after a
federal judge's ruling that cancelled a 1990 Telebras share subscription.
The ruling has to be ratified by a second judge next week. Telebras
preferred fell 1.5 per cent to RDollars 52.
