<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / International Company News: Exxon to issue credit card with
GE Capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Exxon yesterday became the second US energy group to launch a co-branded
credit card, following Shell Oil a year ago.
The move also represents the biggest step by GE Capital, the financial
services group which is issuing the card, into the co-branded credit card
sector, the fastest-growing part of the card market. Until now, the
financial services group has specialised in issuing private-label cards for
retailers. Its only co-branded card has been for General Electric, its
parent.
Service stations represent a big potential market for general purpose credit
cards. At present, there are about 117m private-label cards issued by oil
companies, which can be used only in their own outlets and which account for
annual payments of Dollars 27bn.
Exxon sold its own private-label card business to GE Capital last December.
Yesterday, the financial services company said it did not believe the new
co-branded card, which carries the MasterCard logo, would compete directly
with that business.
Cardholders, who will not pay an annual fee, will receive a rebate of 3 per
cent on purchases made in Exxon's 9,400 stations, and 1 per cent on other
purchases.
</TEXT>
